WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.380
SPEAKER 1: And I have not only
the pleasure, but the privilege

00:00:09.380 --> 00:00:11.690
of introducing Shanthi,
and we're going

00:00:11.690 --> 00:00:13.260
to be having a talk today.

00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:16.400
So before we get started,
I want to read a quick bio.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:18.980
So Shanthi Sekaran
teaches creative writing

00:00:18.980 --> 00:00:20.750
at the California
College of Arts

00:00:20.750 --> 00:00:23.720
and is a member of the San
Francisco Writers' Grotto.

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:26.240
Her work has appeared in
"The New York Times," "Best

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:28.760
New American Voices,"
and "Huffington Post,"

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:31.934
and online at "Zyzzyva"
and "Mutha Magazine."

00:00:31.934 --> 00:00:33.350
Her first novel,
"The Prayer Room"

00:00:33.350 --> 00:00:35.640
was published by MacAdam Cage.

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:37.940
She is a California native
who lives in Berkeley

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:39.562
with her husband
and two children.

00:00:39.562 --> 00:00:42.020
And today, we're going to be
talking about her book, "Lucky

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:45.710
Boy," which follows two stories,
that of Soli Castro-Valdez,

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:49.720
an undocumented Mexican woman,
and that of Rishi and Kavya

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:53.100
Reddy, an Indian-American
couple who live in Berkeley,

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:54.230
California, as well.

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:56.160
Please welcome me
in joining Shanthi.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:57.660
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:02.920
So we'll go ahead and
start off by thanking

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:03.970
Shanthi for being here.

00:01:03.970 --> 00:01:06.511
I had the pleasure of meeting
with her a couple of weeks ago,

00:01:06.511 --> 00:01:08.150
so I'm particularly
excited for today.

00:01:08.150 --> 00:01:09.919
But I'd love to just
start with maybe

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:11.710
reading a couple of
excerpts from the book.

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:12.626
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Sure.

00:01:12.626 --> 00:01:15.220
Yeah, so I'm going to read
two excerpts from the two

00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:16.840
sides of the story.

00:01:16.840 --> 00:01:18.970
So one side is--

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:22.600
one of my main characters is
an undocumented, young Mexican

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:26.440
woman who crosses into
California from Mexico.

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:28.420
She's from Oaxaca, Mexico.

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:33.690
And she ends up in Berkeley,
California, not far from here.

00:01:33.690 --> 00:01:37.240
So Soli-- I don't think you need
to know much else about her.

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:42.760
She's crossing the border,
just getting close to it

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:46.510
in this scene that I'm
about to read right now.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:49.670
And she's met a man
named Checo on her way.

00:01:49.670 --> 00:01:54.340
She had sort of a romance
on her journey up.

00:01:54.340 --> 00:01:58.860
So that's all you need
to know, and here we go.

00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:01.200
"It had been five days
since Soli had last

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:03.990
seen Checo, and thoughts
of him, and what

00:02:03.990 --> 00:02:06.420
might have happened
to him, jangled inside

00:02:06.420 --> 00:02:08.490
her like shards of tin.

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:11.520
Soli and two other women sat
on the bed of a yellow onion

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:14.820
truck, with crates stacked
high to shield them.

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:17.160
Every now and then,
a thin whistle of air

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:20.400
made it through the slats of
the truck and past the crates,

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:22.830
and for those swift
seconds, she sensed

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:25.050
the sweet nearness of the end.

00:02:25.050 --> 00:02:28.080
With the air, the morning
light, the company

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:32.350
of calm woman among who she
could, at last, close her eyes,

00:02:32.350 --> 00:02:35.370
Soli felt that she
would hold together,

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:38.850
cohered by a single strip
of hope, just long enough

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:41.430
to arrive at Silvia's door.

00:02:41.430 --> 00:02:43.950
They stopped twice that day to
piss on the side of the road

00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:45.410
and stretch their legs.

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:48.390
Soli slept-- for how
long, she did not know.

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:50.530
She did not dream of
what had happened to her.

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:54.360
She did not dream of Checo or of
the brutish men who came later.

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:56.660
The cave between
her legs was numb,

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:58.440
but her thighs were
sticky and began

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:00.390
to blister in the day's heat.

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:03.840
When she awoke,
the air was still.

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:08.730
A woman named Luz squinted at
her across the mound of onions.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:10.830
'Where are you
going?' she asked.

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:12.960
'Berkely,' Soli answered.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.410
'Where's that?' 'Close
to San Francisco.'

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:18.060
'You know someone there?'

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:21.876
'Yes, my cousin.' 'Your
cousin have money?'

00:03:21.876 --> 00:03:23.010
'Yes, I think so.

00:03:23.010 --> 00:03:25.500
I think she has the money.'

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:29.840
Luz shook her head like she did
not see good things for Soli.

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:33.290
A few hours after dark, the
driver stopped the truck

00:03:33.290 --> 00:03:35.360
and stuck his head
out his window.

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:37.400
'Get flat,' he called.

00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:38.660
'What's he talking about?'

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:39.710
Soli asked.

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:42.740
Luz rolled herself into a ball.

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:46.370
The truck slowed to a
halt. The engine stopped.

00:03:46.370 --> 00:03:48.980
'Get down,' she hissed, and
pulled sleeping Fatima from

00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:51.790
the bench to the floor.

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:54.100
'Are we here?' Soli asked.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:56.270
'Quiet, make yourself small.'

00:03:56.270 --> 00:03:58.690
Through the crates
in the slats, Soli

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:01.630
saw the flicker of a
dark green uniform.

00:04:01.630 --> 00:04:03.670
The flicker spoke in English.

00:04:03.670 --> 00:04:06.310
He spoke in English.

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:08.750
'We're here,' Soli whispered.

00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:12.350
'Shut up.' Luz was kneeling
beside her and she took

00:04:12.350 --> 00:04:13.910
Soli's hand in hers.

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:16.040
She slipped her fingers
along Soli's knuckles

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:17.660
like they were rosary beads.

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:19.820
And Soli prayed
silently, thinking

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:22.190
of her own lost rosary.

00:04:22.190 --> 00:04:24.650
Though his words were
muffled by onions,

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:27.920
she knew the uniformed man
was questioning their driver.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.460
Shuffling paper, more questions,
and before she could move,

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:33.380
a stick shot through the slats.

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:34.580
She gasped.

00:04:34.580 --> 00:04:36.110
It grazed her skull.

00:04:36.110 --> 00:04:39.160
Again and again, it
rammed through the slats.

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:42.680
A guard's iron wand,
trawling for migrant flesh,

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:44.360
hoping to hit
something live enough

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:49.430
to cry out and prove the truck
carried more than onions.

00:04:49.430 --> 00:04:52.040
She held her hands to
her head and prayed.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:54.800
She knew she was shaking,
but luckily for her, fear

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:56.360
made no sound.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:59.600
Moments later, she heard
footsteps crunch away

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:01.240
and vanish.

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:04.870
The engine started up again,
and they rolled forward.

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:08.260
Luz released a tremulous breath.

00:05:08.260 --> 00:05:09.760
'Lucky,' she said.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:11.350
'A lazy one.'

00:05:11.350 --> 00:05:14.290
She looked up at Soli,
grinned, and pushed her tongue

00:05:14.290 --> 00:05:17.430
through the gap in her teeth.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:19.000
'We're here.'

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.310
'In the North?' 'America, mija.

00:05:22.310 --> 00:05:23.590
That's what they call it here.

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:25.850
We are in California now.'

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:27.950
Soli looked up to the sky--

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:30.350
same blue as the Mexican sky.

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:32.300
She looked through
the truck slats.

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:35.960
This was California, the
United States of America.

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:39.770
She had arrived, and
here's what she discovered.

00:05:39.770 --> 00:05:44.090
This place, this
America, this new place,

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:47.330
this streets of gold place,
looked a hell of a lot

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:49.160
like the old place.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.940
America streaked by her
stripped and tender with heat.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:55.190
She watched it all rush
past through the slats

00:05:55.190 --> 00:05:56.360
of the old truck--

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.940
the tin roofs, seas
of broken glass,

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:02.180
glinting and breathless
like a fever dream.

00:06:02.180 --> 00:06:05.870
America was the dust in her
hair, the wind in her throat,

00:06:05.870 --> 00:06:08.720
the sun that shouted
against her eyelids.

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:11.240
Between the slats of
this truck, America

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:13.670
was nothing but a
high-tech, high-speed dream

00:06:13.670 --> 00:06:19.680
of trees and houses and fences,
a sliver of interrupted light.

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.710
The old folks back home, those
who'd been here and back,

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:25.890
told Soli she would do well
here, that she had the spirit.

00:06:25.890 --> 00:06:28.740
They told her to keep her
head down and work hard,

00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:32.198
and for God's sake,
keep her mouth shut."

00:06:32.198 --> 00:06:32.698
OK.

00:06:32.698 --> 00:06:34.174
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:38.120 --> 00:06:39.680
So that's Soli.

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:42.470
The other side of
my story is a couple

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:44.480
named Kavya and Rishi Reddy.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:45.450
They live in Berkeley.

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:48.050
And Kavya's a chef
at a sorority,

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:49.880
which is its own story.

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:55.700
But Rishi is a worker at
a Silicon Valley company.

00:06:55.700 --> 00:06:58.790
He does stuff with air
quality in buildings.

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:01.380
So he works for this gigantic
Silicon Valley company

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:02.030
that I made up.

00:07:02.030 --> 00:07:03.590
It's called the Weebies.

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:05.750
And it's one of these--

00:07:05.750 --> 00:07:09.320
it's a company that just--
it's like a gigantic Amazon

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:12.080
for children's and
babies' supplies,

00:07:12.080 --> 00:07:16.190
combined with some
social networking stuff.

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:21.790
So this little bit is
going to be a little bit

00:07:21.790 --> 00:07:25.240
from Kavya's point of view, but
then we're going to transition

00:07:25.240 --> 00:07:27.790
into Rishi's point of view.

00:07:27.790 --> 00:07:30.800
And here we go.

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:33.440
"Despite the clarity
of her desire,

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:37.190
Kavya had no real idea of
what sort of mother she'd be.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:40.640
The parents around her seemed to
take great pride in their work,

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:43.100
like artisans of a dying craft.

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.040
Jogging through parks and
waiting in BART stations,

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:48.650
Kavya had come across
American mothers speaking

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:52.040
French to their American
children, fathers explaining

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:53.930
the physics of
underground transport

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:56.210
to their preschoolers,
property tax

00:07:56.210 --> 00:07:58.190
law to their eight-year-olds.

00:07:58.190 --> 00:08:01.100
At the farmer's market the
week before, a little girl

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:03.110
had fallen and scraped her knee.

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:06.170
As she stood sobbing,
inconsolable, her mother

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:07.940
knelt down beside her.

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:08.670
'Here, sweetie.

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:09.500
Have some kale.'

00:08:13.630 --> 00:08:15.650
The little girl had
taken it, chewed

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:19.580
on the tough, primordial
leaf, and stopped crying.

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:21.500
The stakes were
high in Berkeley.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:25.257
The toddlers were eating
their cruciferous greens.

00:08:25.257 --> 00:08:27.590
There were things she couldn't
know about being a parent

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:28.980
without being one.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:30.920
This, she sensed from
the way men and women

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:34.010
with children in tow seemed
to have little to say to her.

00:08:34.010 --> 00:08:37.010
Parenthood was a members-only
organization closed

00:08:37.010 --> 00:08:39.320
to freelancers and temps.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:41.690
Outsiders could visit
for lunch, but they

00:08:41.690 --> 00:08:44.480
tended to leave quickly,
overwhelmed by the demands

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:45.930
of belonging.

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:47.840
But Kavya didn't want to leave.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:50.970
Kavya wanted in.

00:08:50.970 --> 00:08:54.920
For Rishi, the brilliant
bonus of this new world,

00:08:54.920 --> 00:08:59.430
this procreative world, was
a sudden abundance of sex.

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:01.650
They were doing it every
day, sometimes twice,

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:03.480
like they'd done
in the early days.

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:06.060
They had sex for lunch and
ate burritos in the car.

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:08.760
They had sex in the living room
and toppled the throw pillows

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:09.870
from the sofa.

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:12.540
They had sex in a restaurant
once, in the bathroom,

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:14.650
and once in a parking lot.

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:16.680
But after two
months, then three,

00:09:16.680 --> 00:09:19.470
these trysts began to
feel inappropriate,

00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:21.750
like their control was slipping.

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:24.750
He began to wonder what it was
about, all the spontaneity?

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:26.490
He supposed Kavya
was trying to keep

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:28.890
things fun, maybe
even for his sake,

00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:32.490
to combat the impatience
that lurked in the shadows.

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:36.210
For three months, Kavya
refused to look at her calendar

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:38.880
or take her temperature, or do
any of the things a woman did

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:40.770
to track their fertility.

00:09:40.770 --> 00:09:42.360
'It shouldn't matter,' she said.

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:44.280
It should just happen.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:46.110
But then it didn't just happen.

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:48.360
After three months of
trying and failing,

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:50.640
the sex could no
longer be casual.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:52.260
She began taking
her temperature,

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:54.380
tracking her ovulation.

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:56.320
Rishi had been on
board with this.

00:09:56.320 --> 00:09:58.470
He would think of it as
a project, he decided.

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:00.300
Project managing
was what he did,

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:02.010
and driving his
management approach

00:10:02.010 --> 00:10:05.670
was the Weebies principle,
the Silicon Valley principle

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:08.160
that nothing was impossible.

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:11.000
Impossibility was not
an absolute, but as

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.140
shiftable as a heavy boulder.

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:15.900
Trial and error and a
little cognitive daring

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:19.410
were all it took to make
the impossible, possible.

00:10:19.410 --> 00:10:23.280
It had worked for PCs,
the internet, smartphones.

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:26.070
It would work for his baby.

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:28.470
Sex whenever became
sex on a schedule.

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:31.920
Kavya felt a sense of
purpose, satisfaction even.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:33.600
She was taking charge.

00:10:33.600 --> 00:10:36.570
Kavya began demanding sex as
Rishi hurried from the house

00:10:36.570 --> 00:10:38.580
to catch the Weebus.

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:41.340
She once actually drove
out to the Weebies campus

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:43.380
and showed up at
his office door.

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:45.510
'I'm ovulating right
now,' she said.

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:47.360
'Like, now.'

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:49.470
Rishi had found them
a nap room, disobeying

00:10:49.470 --> 00:10:51.840
the strict single
occupant limit.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:53.550
They'd emerged
flushed and rumpled

00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:55.890
in full view few of
his coworkers gathered

00:10:55.890 --> 00:10:58.320
at the espresso machine.

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:01.630
Often, from across the Bay,
she'd text him in all caps--

00:11:01.630 --> 00:11:04.380
mid-meeting, mid-presentation,
mid-epiphany--

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.420
to say, 'COME HOME.

00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:09.130
I NEED YOU NOW.'

00:11:09.130 --> 00:11:10.870
What once would
have thrilled Rishi

00:11:10.870 --> 00:11:16.040
stirred in him a sense of
anxiety, futility, ingratitude.

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:19.990
He felt less like a man and
more like an indentured servant,

00:11:19.990 --> 00:11:22.600
keeping up his end
of a shady bargain.

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:26.030
And every time, every month
they tried to get pregnant,

00:11:26.030 --> 00:11:28.690
Rishi watched Kavya
grow more brittle.

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:31.120
He thought of himself
as a rational person,

00:11:31.120 --> 00:11:35.340
good at compartmentalizing, good
at avoiding flights of fancy.

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:37.390
But trying to have a
baby defied his powers

00:11:37.390 --> 00:11:40.240
of reason and
strategy and desire.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:43.420
He bought into the idea
that hard work bred success,

00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:45.970
but Rishi and Kavya
were working hard.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:48.790
They were working
unnaturally hard at this most

00:11:48.790 --> 00:11:51.560
natural of tasks.

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:53.960
Six months passed
and still nothing,

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:57.970
nine months, and Kavya had found
herself at Prithi's wedding.

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:02.140
And now 10-- the gravel in her
throat had grown to a stone.

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:04.060
Every time she saw
a baby or a woman

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:05.980
with a luscious
globe of a belly,

00:12:05.980 --> 00:12:08.720
the stone grew
harder and larger.

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:10.330
But Kavya knew this much--

00:12:10.330 --> 00:12:11.500
she was a woman.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.120
She was an Indian woman.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:15.070
Surely a country
with 1 billion people

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:17.560
had produced some capable wombs.

00:12:17.560 --> 00:12:19.660
She was going to have a baby.

00:12:19.660 --> 00:12:21.520
She and Rishi just
needed to get away

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:24.880
from the theater of failure
that had become their bedroom.

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:28.090
They needed to escape the
chilly corners of their bungalow

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.040
and have the sort of
relaxed intercourse

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:32.680
from which babies
seemed to spring.

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:36.520
Her ears buzzed with certainty
and farther inside, her ovaries

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:37.660
winced.

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:39.460
She texted Rishi.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:43.140
'Napa Valley, this
weekend, spa, B&amp;B--

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:45.590
I'm booking it!'

00:12:45.590 --> 00:12:48.590
The exclamation
mark, so hopeful,

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:52.470
she began to delete it,
then decided to let it be."

00:12:52.470 --> 00:12:54.410
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:57.320 --> 00:12:59.150
SPEAKER 1: Wonderful,
thank you so much.

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:00.830
I don't know about those
of you that heard it,

00:13:00.830 --> 00:13:02.705
but I went through the
full range of emotions

00:13:02.705 --> 00:13:05.360
from, the powerful, beautiful
descriptive language

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:06.685
in the first one to--

00:13:06.685 --> 00:13:09.934
I don't know, the second segment
