00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:13.970
in the Bay Area, in general.

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:15.560
So before we go
into "Lucky Boy,"

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:18.639
I'd love to just hear about
your beginning as an author.

00:13:18.639 --> 00:13:19.680
What's that journey like?

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:21.835
Did you always know
you wanted to write?

00:13:21.835 --> 00:13:23.210
SHANTHI SEKARAN:
I did not always

00:13:23.210 --> 00:13:24.376
know that I wanted to write.

00:13:24.376 --> 00:13:25.619
I knew that I loved books.

00:13:25.619 --> 00:13:26.660
And I think my brothers--

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:28.118
I have these two
older brothers who

00:13:28.118 --> 00:13:30.679
are 10 years and 11
years older than me--

00:13:30.679 --> 00:13:31.970
I think they knew before I did.

00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:33.350
We used to play "Fresh Air."

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:36.057
We used to pretend we were
on "Fresh Air" together.

00:13:36.057 --> 00:13:37.640
Like, my brother
would be Terry Gross,

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:40.280
and I would be me,
talking about a book.

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:42.830
And so I think
they had some sense

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:44.030
that this was what I loved.

00:13:44.030 --> 00:13:47.330
But I'd spent a lot
of my school years

00:13:47.330 --> 00:13:49.820
thinking I was going to
be an English literature

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:54.750
professor, until I realized
how theoretical that field is.

00:13:54.750 --> 00:13:57.710
And what I loved was the books
and the language and talking

00:13:57.710 --> 00:13:58.880
about that.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:01.550
So it was really only
when I was about 22

00:14:01.550 --> 00:14:04.730
that I had started
writing creatively,

00:14:04.730 --> 00:14:09.290
and took, really, just the
first pages of my first attempts

00:14:09.290 --> 00:14:13.130
at creative writing and sent
those into an MFA program.

00:14:13.130 --> 00:14:17.510
And got in-- got into
one, and went to that one,

00:14:17.510 --> 00:14:20.120
and took it from there,
just to sort of see if this

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:22.550
was something that I could do.

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:25.280
And so it was a slow process,
but the love of books

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:26.120
was always there.

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:27.162
SPEAKER 1: I love that.

00:14:27.162 --> 00:14:27.870
That's wonderful.

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.786
Yeah, I feel like we're
all-- at least for me,

00:14:29.786 --> 00:14:32.420
I'm still trying to figure
out what is the niche, what

00:14:32.420 --> 00:14:33.359
is the thing to do.

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:35.150
I love hearing from
authors, their journey,

00:14:35.150 --> 00:14:36.691
because it ranges
from always knowing

00:14:36.691 --> 00:14:38.360
that you wanted to
write to just one

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:40.352
day, realizing that
it's your passion.

00:14:40.352 --> 00:14:41.810
And in terms of
genre, did you ever

00:14:41.810 --> 00:14:43.351
think about what
you wanted to write,

00:14:43.351 --> 00:14:46.424
whether it was fiction or
nonfiction, particular topics--

00:14:46.424 --> 00:14:48.590
SHANTHI SEKARAN: I'd always
wanted to write fiction.

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.120
I think poetry is kind of scary.

00:14:50.120 --> 00:14:51.450
I really admire poets.

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:54.420
But really, there's no
safety net with poetry.

00:14:54.420 --> 00:14:57.890
You're really putting
yourself out there.

00:14:57.890 --> 00:15:00.530
Nonfiction-- this
was the closest

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:03.990
I've ever come to
nonfiction, as a writer.

00:15:03.990 --> 00:15:08.420
So this took a lot of
research, and I now feel

00:15:08.420 --> 00:15:10.610
like more adept at nonfiction.

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:12.320
I feel like I can go
in that direction,

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:14.750
but it took a sort
of transitional book,

00:15:14.750 --> 00:15:16.040
like "Lucky Boy."

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:17.456
SPEAKER 1: Yeah,
so it's wonderful

00:15:17.456 --> 00:15:20.060
because it is a fiction book,
and yet there are so many areas

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:21.890
that, when you and I
chatted, you really

00:15:21.890 --> 00:15:24.507
wanted to explore to make
sure that you do it justice.

00:15:24.507 --> 00:15:26.090
So do you mind telling
us a little bit

00:15:26.090 --> 00:15:27.548
about your preparation
and learning

00:15:27.548 --> 00:15:30.170
about tech companies,
immigration, the Latinx

00:15:30.170 --> 00:15:31.340
experience?

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:33.350
SHANTHI SEKARAN:
Yeah, so I was faced

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:38.780
with this task of writing
these worlds that I was not

00:15:38.780 --> 00:15:42.050
familiar with, from Soli's world
to the Silicon Valley world

00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:44.510
to fertility issues.

00:15:44.510 --> 00:15:48.020
So I started very basic
with some documentaries

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:50.150
and oral histories,
just getting a sense

00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:52.370
of what the undocumented
experience might

00:15:52.370 --> 00:15:55.110
be like for people, what it's
like to cross the border,

00:15:55.110 --> 00:15:58.340
why people feel they
need to leave their homes

00:15:58.340 --> 00:16:01.460
and come to America.

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:06.680
It started pretty sort of
straightforward in that way,

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:08.925
and then I started to
just look for people

00:16:08.925 --> 00:16:09.800
who would talk to me.

00:16:09.800 --> 00:16:13.670
So immigration lawyers,
immigration policy scholars,

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:16.190
adoptive parents, because
Kavya and Rishi end up

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:18.690
being foster parents
to Soli's child.

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:23.700
Yeah, so in all of
these realms, people

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:25.330
who'd undergone
fertility treatments,

00:16:25.330 --> 00:16:29.520
just anyone who would talk
to me about their experience,

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:30.855
I tried to get a hold of.

00:16:30.855 --> 00:16:31.980
And people are pretty open.

00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:33.813
When you're a novelist
and not a journalist,

00:16:33.813 --> 00:16:36.670
people are pretty
willing to talk to you.

00:16:36.670 --> 00:16:40.020
And with Silicon
Valley, I spent a day--

00:16:40.020 --> 00:16:42.270
less, like, a few hours
here with Ann Less,

00:16:42.270 --> 00:16:46.530
who's here, and just kind of
went to lunch in the cafeteria,

00:16:46.530 --> 00:16:48.600
walked around a little.

00:16:48.600 --> 00:16:50.550
I've never worked
in Silicon Valley.

00:16:50.550 --> 00:16:51.840
So a lot of--

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:55.080
I think I absorbed
literally 37 details

00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:58.200
and put them all in this book.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.180
During those few hours--
and then, just living

00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:02.670
in California, it's
part of the zeitgeist.

00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:04.260
You absorb stuff, as well.

00:17:04.260 --> 00:17:06.140
SPEAKER 1: Yeah,
that's wonderful.

