00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:32.076
And as I was reading
through this,

00:17:32.076 --> 00:17:33.770
I was like, this is so accurate.

00:17:33.770 --> 00:17:35.650
You did a great job
of capturing it.

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:37.190
So speaking of
tech, obviously it's

00:17:37.190 --> 00:17:39.420
a predominant part of the book.

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:43.440
What role do you think tech has
as an industry in this topic,

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:45.570
in immigration?

00:17:45.570 --> 00:17:49.110
SHANTHI SEKARAN: What role
does tech have in immigration?

00:17:49.110 --> 00:17:53.100
I've been thinking about the
H-1B issues that have been

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:55.660
coming up in the past few days.

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:57.930
And I see tech as the new--

00:17:57.930 --> 00:18:00.630
it is the new
industry in the world,

00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:03.210
and especially in California.

00:18:03.210 --> 00:18:05.960
And it needs people.

00:18:05.960 --> 00:18:08.730
It needs people who are capable.

00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:12.300
And we're such a
globalized society now,

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:14.220
that immigration and tech--

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:16.950
immigration feeds
tech, at this point.

00:18:16.950 --> 00:18:20.370
And I feel like that's
the way it should be.

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:25.500
And on the other side of
it, being one of our biggest

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:28.590
industries right
now, I feel like tech

00:18:28.590 --> 00:18:32.700
might have a role to play in--

00:18:32.700 --> 00:18:35.640
I don't know, in having a
say in some of these issues

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:36.780
and issues of immigration?

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:38.280
I'm not all that
actually completely

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:40.410
certain what I think of that.

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:42.480
I don't know if business
should stay away

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:47.490
from politics, if business
should stay away from issues

00:18:47.490 --> 00:18:49.280
of immigration or not.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:51.930
I'd sort of be interested
to hear what people think,

00:18:51.930 --> 00:18:52.790
being in this world.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:54.540
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, we'll
have an opportunity

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:56.925
to get some
questions, maybe even

00:18:56.925 --> 00:18:58.830
some opinions from the group.

00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:01.430
So speaking more
about immigration,

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:05.100
there is a lot of themes in
the book about immigration

00:19:05.100 --> 00:19:09.314
intersecting with motherhood
or parenthood or family.

00:19:09.314 --> 00:19:11.730
I feel like often in our nation,
we talk about immigration

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:13.990
as an individual topic.

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:16.890
So what opportunities do
we have to view immigration

00:19:16.890 --> 00:19:19.862
from that more family or
motherhood perspective?

00:19:19.862 --> 00:19:22.320
SHANTHI SEKARAN: So one thing
that I found out pretty early

00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:28.440
on is that of our 11 million
undocumented immigrants,

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:32.970
within that statistic, 5
million children in the US

00:19:32.970 --> 00:19:36.670
have at least one
undocumented parent.

00:19:36.670 --> 00:19:38.610
So we think of
immigration, you're right,

00:19:38.610 --> 00:19:40.770
as a very individual pursuit.

00:19:40.770 --> 00:19:44.610
America was built on these
ideas of individualism

00:19:44.610 --> 00:19:50.860
versus collectivism and
this idea of bootstraps,

00:19:50.860 --> 00:19:54.430
and just being your own person
and forging your own way,

00:19:54.430 --> 00:19:56.470
which is all very admirable.

00:19:56.470 --> 00:19:59.620
But it's worth noting
that these issues--

00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:01.690
when we talk about
undocumented immigrants,

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:04.030
we're not talking about
the one immigrant who

00:20:04.030 --> 00:20:06.250
crosses the border on his own.

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:08.830
We're talking about
the family that he

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:12.860
might build in the US,
his family back home.

00:20:12.860 --> 00:20:16.030
We're talking about
generations, of ramifications

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:19.488
for whatever we decide
to do with immigration.

00:20:19.488 --> 00:20:21.280
SPEAKER 1:
Definitely, and I like

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:24.010
that you're talking about
that because we often

00:20:24.010 --> 00:20:26.200
think of an image when we
think of immigrant, right?

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:30.770
And it's often the unlucky,
right, or the unfortunate,

00:20:30.770 --> 00:20:33.440
or having to deal with
the same struggles.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:35.440
But we have immigrants
from all over the world,

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:38.290
and they come with
different experiences.

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:40.970
You wrote an op-ed in "The
New York Times" called

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:42.585
"The Privileged Immigrant."

00:20:42.585 --> 00:20:44.710
Do you mind talking a little
bit about that article

00:20:44.710 --> 00:20:48.130
and how that correlates with
what "Lucky Boy" tells us,

00:20:48.130 --> 00:20:48.940
as well?

00:20:48.940 --> 00:20:51.280
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Yeah, so
"The Privileged Immigrant,"

00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:52.810
that came out in November.

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:54.460
And it, basically,
is a discussion

00:20:54.460 --> 00:20:58.600
of my own family's
immigration experience, which

00:20:58.600 --> 00:21:01.060
was that my parents
came over in the 1960s

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:02.830
as foreign medical graduates.

00:21:02.830 --> 00:21:05.590
My dad had graduated medical
school at that point,

00:21:05.590 --> 00:21:11.320
and the US was trying to fill
its hospitals with its Medicare

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:14.350
network that had just
been put in place.

00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:18.220
So that article sort of looks
at their experience of yes,

00:21:18.220 --> 00:21:21.460
being alienated, yes,
struggling a lot,

00:21:21.460 --> 00:21:25.960
but at least having solid
work and having a visa,

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:30.400
having a solid, legal
way to be in the US.

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:33.530
And that not only put them
at ease psychologically,

00:21:33.530 --> 00:21:36.490
but it allowed them to
put structures in place

00:21:36.490 --> 00:21:39.590
in their lives that have brought
them where they are today.

00:21:39.590 --> 00:21:41.800
It allowed them to
start savings accounts

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:45.010
and start investing
and buy property.

00:21:45.010 --> 00:21:48.640
And we see I enjoy the
fruits of that now,

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:50.240
and my kids enjoy
the fruits of that.

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:53.310
So again, we're going
forward for generations.

00:21:53.310 --> 00:21:57.490
And when you think about
an undocumented immigrant,

00:21:57.490 --> 00:22:00.580
there are structures in place
for undocumented immigrants.

00:22:00.580 --> 00:22:03.820
They can go to a bank
and open a bank account,

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:06.640
but it's terrifying
to walk into a bank.

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:09.370
We saw what just happened
to the first DACA

00:22:09.370 --> 00:22:13.240
recipient who was deported.

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:17.560
It's scary to go in and give
your official information

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:20.560
to an institution when
you don't actually

00:22:20.560 --> 00:22:23.770
belong here with legal papers.

00:22:23.770 --> 00:22:27.550
So it's really hard for
undocumented immigrants,

00:22:27.550 --> 00:22:32.350
I realized, while researching
this book to put those building

00:22:32.350 --> 00:22:36.100
blocks in place for
a stable future.

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:38.530
SPEAKER 1: And how much of
your own personal experiences

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:40.210
would you say
influenced this book?

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:42.730
Because the first book
that you wrote also

00:22:42.730 --> 00:22:44.730
had a lot of your personal
experiences, as well.

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:46.300
So I'd love to see
how much of that

00:22:46.300 --> 00:22:47.750
you incorporate in your writing.

00:22:47.750 --> 00:22:50.440
SHANTHI SEKARAN: So my
personal experiences--

00:22:50.440 --> 00:22:53.560
in order to start
to understand Soli,

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:56.290
I had to understand
her in my terms.

00:22:56.290 --> 00:22:59.480
I had to relate to
her as a person.

00:22:59.480 --> 00:23:01.000
And so motherhood
is in here a lot.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.100
I have two kids.

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:05.350
There's some material
right after the little boy

00:23:05.350 --> 00:23:07.120
is born in this book
that comes straight

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:09.580
from what I had jotted down
right after my little boy was

00:23:09.580 --> 00:23:11.290
born.

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:15.490
And then the ideas of
immigration and, particularly

00:23:15.490 --> 00:23:20.050
with Kavya and Rishi, these
ideas of ambition and what

00:23:20.050 --> 00:23:23.380
parents want for their children
and what it's like for a second

00:23:23.380 --> 00:23:27.730
generation Indian-American or
a second generation immigrant,

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:29.770
there is this unspoken--

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:34.000
sometimes spoken-- agreement
between immigrant parents

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.740
and their children,
which basically says,

00:23:36.740 --> 00:23:40.970
look, I gave up everything
I knew to come over here.

00:23:40.970 --> 00:23:42.595
So you'd better do
something with this.

00:23:45.220 --> 00:23:51.070
And so failure is not, in
many parents' view, an option.

00:23:51.070 --> 00:23:55.000
So that fed into Kavya's
experience in the story

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:57.970
and it fed into
Rishi's experience.

00:23:57.970 --> 00:24:01.014
And it also fed into the
narrative around fertility

00:24:01.014 --> 00:24:02.305
and being able to have a child.

00:24:02.305 --> 00:24:05.930
SPEAKER 1: Mm-hmm,
that's wonderful.

00:24:05.930 --> 00:24:08.170
I also know that
when we were talking,

00:24:08.170 --> 00:24:09.790
we were talking a
lot about the things

00:24:09.790 --> 00:24:11.859
that you learned when
you were doing research.

00:24:11.859 --> 00:24:13.900
And particularly, when
looking at the differences

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:17.080
in immigrants, there was
the detention centers

00:24:17.080 --> 00:24:19.249
that you observed, and you
learned a lot about that.

00:24:19.249 --> 00:24:21.040
Can you tell us more
about that experience,

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:23.950
what it was like to see what
undocumented immigrants go

00:24:23.950 --> 00:24:25.330
through?

00:24:25.330 --> 00:24:27.670
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Yes, so
I trained with a group

00:24:27.670 --> 00:24:32.290
called CIVIC Endisolation,
and they do a lot of work

00:24:32.290 --> 00:24:34.210
with undocumented immigrants.

00:24:34.210 --> 00:24:37.390
They started out sort of
providing legal representation

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:39.670
because when you're
in a detention center,

00:24:39.670 --> 00:24:41.617
you're not given
a defense lawyer.

00:24:41.617 --> 00:24:42.700
You're not given a lawyer.

00:24:42.700 --> 00:24:47.770
It's not like being
a criminal in the US.

00:24:47.770 --> 00:24:51.520
So they were helping people
A, find their families,

00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:58.420
and also try to get some
legal aid for their situation.

00:24:58.420 --> 00:25:02.350
And when I trained with them, I
visited the detention facility

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:05.080
out in Richmond, California.

00:25:05.080 --> 00:25:06.460
And it was just--

00:25:06.460 --> 00:25:10.450
I didn't get to see where
people were actually living.

00:25:10.450 --> 00:25:13.600
And the Richmond facility
is a somewhat reformed one,

00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:16.300
people have a little
more room to wander.

00:25:16.300 --> 00:25:18.050
They can leave their
rooms when they want.

00:25:18.050 --> 00:25:20.020
They have a little more freedom.

00:25:20.020 --> 00:25:23.830
But a lot of what I learned
about the detention centers

00:25:23.830 --> 00:25:27.640
came from writings,
lawyers who have

00:25:27.640 --> 00:25:30.190
devoted their careers to
researching different detention

00:25:30.190 --> 00:25:31.270
centers.

00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:34.360
And much of what I learned
revolved around the fact

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:37.450
that detention centers
are basically prisons.

00:25:37.450 --> 00:25:41.410
They're often within the
prison facility, itself.

00:25:41.410 --> 00:25:43.990
But they're like prisons
without facilities,

00:25:43.990 --> 00:25:46.710
because it's not
considered permanent,

00:25:46.710 --> 00:25:50.930
a long-term solution
for an immigrant,

00:25:50.930 --> 00:25:52.820
so they don't give
you resources.

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:55.150
So if you're a
parent in detention,

00:25:55.150 --> 00:25:58.510
and you're separated from
your American-born child,

00:25:58.510 --> 00:26:00.340
there's nothing
there that allows

00:26:00.340 --> 00:26:03.970
you to reunite with your child.

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:06.460
So if a family
court says, OK, we

00:26:06.460 --> 00:26:08.980
want you to do this
and this and this

00:26:08.980 --> 00:26:11.546
to qualify for
reunification, there's

00:26:11.546 --> 00:26:13.420
no way a detainee can
do that because there's

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:16.378
nothing in the center for them.

00:26:16.378 --> 00:26:18.250
SPEAKER 1: Wow.

00:26:18.250 --> 00:26:20.007
So the research behind it--

00:26:20.007 --> 00:26:22.090
I mean, I was so impressed
with the amount of work

00:26:22.090 --> 00:26:24.982
that went into finding out,
understanding that experience.

00:26:24.982 --> 00:26:26.440
And actually, you
were just talking

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:28.540
about this, that the
story beautifully

00:26:28.540 --> 00:26:31.540
contrasts two different
journeys of immigrants that

00:26:31.540 --> 00:26:33.520
have different experiences.

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:36.310
Our nation often tends to
privilege certain minorities

00:26:36.310 --> 00:26:38.390
over others.

00:26:38.390 --> 00:26:42.010
And what I liked is that
you were treading lightly.

00:26:42.010 --> 00:26:44.500
You wanted to dig deep and get
information about the Latinx

00:26:44.500 --> 00:26:47.110
experience, but you wanted to
make sure that you did it well.

00:26:47.110 --> 00:26:49.750
So I personally think
that you took the time

00:26:49.750 --> 00:26:51.950
and you handled it very
eloquently and beautifully.

00:26:51.950 --> 00:26:53.560
And you were-- as
a Latino, I think

00:26:53.560 --> 00:26:55.960
you told the story very well.

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:58.120
But did you ever feel--

00:26:58.120 --> 00:27:01.570
maybe you were-- and
I ask this as the kind

00:27:01.570 --> 00:27:04.300
of contentious
question, in terms

00:27:04.300 --> 00:27:07.240
of cultural appropriation, what
is the fine line between being

00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:09.820
an ally and telling
someone else's

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:11.530
experience from your
perspective to show

00:27:11.530 --> 00:27:14.530
your allieship,
versus potentially

00:27:14.530 --> 00:27:15.805
appropriating that culture?

00:27:15.805 --> 00:27:17.721
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Yeah,
that's a good question.

00:27:17.721 --> 00:27:20.830
I did struggle with this
idea of appropriation

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:23.020
and whether I was
telling someone's story

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:25.720
when I shouldn't be
telling their story.

00:27:25.720 --> 00:27:29.020
So the way I approached
that was, first of all,

00:27:29.020 --> 00:27:32.810
to accept the fact that I
would never truly understand

00:27:32.810 --> 00:27:35.710
Soli, my Mexican character.

00:27:35.710 --> 00:27:38.890
I can never truly understand
the Latinx experience.

00:27:38.890 --> 00:27:44.290
I can never truly understand
the undocumented experience.

00:27:44.290 --> 00:27:47.110
So one thing that I eventually
realized that I had to do

00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:50.680
was after all the research,
which was necessary,

00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:55.630
I had to figure out how
I personally related

00:27:55.630 --> 00:27:58.060
to Soli, to my character.

00:27:58.060 --> 00:28:03.740
And I eventually realized
that this was, essentially,

00:28:03.740 --> 00:28:06.930
a story about a young
woman who became a mother

00:28:06.930 --> 00:28:09.590
and who wanted certain
things for herself.

00:28:09.590 --> 00:28:12.740
And the fact that she
was Latina, the fact

00:28:12.740 --> 00:28:14.840
that she was undocumented--

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:17.780
these all determine the
trajectory of her story,

00:28:17.780 --> 00:28:21.200
but they were not
the story itself.

00:28:21.200 --> 00:28:22.040
So I was able--

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:26.750
I tried to connect
with her in that way.

00:28:26.750 --> 00:28:32.870
And I just had to realize, I
had to accept that I was never

00:28:32.870 --> 00:28:35.270
going to do it complete
justice, and I just

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:36.740
had to tread
carefully and make her

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:38.796
as fully fledged as I could.

00:28:38.796 --> 00:28:40.670
SPEAKER 1: Well, as a
former Spanish teacher,

00:28:40.670 --> 00:28:43.120
your pronunciation of all the
names is absolutely beautiful,

00:28:43.120 --> 00:28:43.500
so I do want to say that.

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:43.600
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Really?

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:44.795
Oh, good.

00:28:44.795 --> 00:28:46.170
SPEAKER 1: It made
me very happy.

00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:47.128
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Great.

00:28:47.128 --> 00:28:49.190
SPEAKER 1: So obviously,
the topic of "Lucky Boy"

00:28:49.190 --> 00:28:51.530
is very timely, not only
internally here at Google,

00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:54.140
but domestically and
globally, particularly

00:28:54.140 --> 00:28:55.680
in the last few months.

00:28:55.680 --> 00:28:58.310
What struggles or
obstacles do you

00:28:58.310 --> 00:29:01.190
feel you face as an author
writing about this topic

00:29:01.190 --> 00:29:02.872
today, in 2017?

00:29:02.872 --> 00:29:04.580
SHANTHI SEKARAN:
Struggles as an author--

00:29:07.700 --> 00:29:10.880
there was this looming question
of cultural appropriation.

00:29:10.880 --> 00:29:15.590
That's a big issue
for us right now.

00:29:15.590 --> 00:29:19.430
I did sort of wonder,
initially, if this book was

00:29:19.430 --> 00:29:21.770
going to be sort of taken up.

00:29:21.770 --> 00:29:25.610
I'm not-- it's not your
classic American novel

00:29:25.610 --> 00:29:30.620
about people in Upper
East Side Manhattan.

00:29:30.620 --> 00:29:32.660
In fact, the people
who are white,

00:29:32.660 --> 00:29:34.940
they're sort of on the
periphery of this book.

00:29:34.940 --> 00:29:37.765
And so I did wonder if that--

00:29:37.765 --> 00:29:40.880
if the fact that I had
this group of brown people

00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:44.420
and this brown woman,
and everyone was brown,

00:29:44.420 --> 00:29:47.330
if that would be sort of
an obstacle to getting it

00:29:47.330 --> 00:29:48.680
published.

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:50.596
And at one point, I
said to my agent--

00:29:50.596 --> 00:29:52.970
it wasn't getting published,
it went through two or three

00:29:52.970 --> 00:29:54.110
rounds of rejections.

00:29:54.110 --> 00:29:56.360
And I said to my agent,
maybe I should just

00:29:56.360 --> 00:29:59.580
make all my Indians white
and see what happens.

00:29:59.580 --> 00:30:01.412
And she was like,
absolutely not.

00:30:01.412 --> 00:30:02.745
SPEAKER 1: Uh, amen to her, wow.

00:30:02.745 --> 00:30:03.700
SHANTHI SEKARAN:
She was like, no.

00:30:03.700 --> 00:30:06.080
Well, she pointed out to
me that this is not just

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:07.220
about a Mexican woman.

00:30:07.220 --> 00:30:12.920
This is a story of immigrants
on American soil in 2000--

00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:13.880
whatever it was then--

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:16.310
2000, the 2000s.

00:30:16.310 --> 00:30:18.860
And so that allowed
me to sort of take

00:30:18.860 --> 00:30:22.305
a new perspective on what
I was doing, so yeah.

00:30:22.305 --> 00:30:23.180
SPEAKER 1: Wonderful.

00:30:23.180 --> 00:30:26.860
So in looking into your
future endeavors, what's next?

00:30:26.860 --> 00:30:28.700
It could be a
specific book, or do

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:30.530
you think you've found
your area and you

00:30:30.530 --> 00:30:33.269
want to continue talking about
the immigrant experience?

00:30:33.269 --> 00:30:35.060
SHANTHI SEKARAN: I kind
of want to do both.

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:38.990
So I'm going to start slowly
working on it on my next book

00:30:38.990 --> 00:30:42.170
as soon as all
this touring ends.

00:30:42.170 --> 00:30:46.010
And I also feel like, you
know, I've written this book,

00:30:46.010 --> 00:30:47.570
so this is what
I'm grappling with.

00:30:47.570 --> 00:30:48.860
I've written this book.

00:30:48.860 --> 00:30:51.269
It's about this topic.

00:30:51.269 --> 00:30:53.810
What, am I just going to drop
it now and talk about something

00:30:53.810 --> 00:30:54.854
else next?

00:30:54.854 --> 00:30:57.020
Because I feel like now
that I've written this book,

00:30:57.020 --> 00:30:58.520
I want to do something
more with it.

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:01.610
I want to actually
use it in some way

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:04.940
to enact some
beginnings of change

00:31:04.940 --> 00:31:06.996
in something that I care about.

00:31:06.996 --> 00:31:08.120
So hopefully, I'll do that.

00:31:08.120 --> 00:31:09.710
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, and
just out of curiosity,

00:31:09.710 --> 00:31:10.940
obviously, you're a writer.

00:31:10.940 --> 00:31:13.610
We're all super
excited that this book

00:31:13.610 --> 00:31:16.130
is out, nothing but
positive feedback,

00:31:16.130 --> 00:31:17.670
at least that I've seen.

00:31:17.670 --> 00:31:20.120
But what are some of
your favorite authors?

00:31:20.120 --> 00:31:21.290
What do you like to read?

00:31:21.290 --> 00:31:23.180
Who do you look up
to, who inspires you?

00:31:23.180 --> 00:31:24.721
SHANTHI SEKARAN: My
favorite author--

00:31:24.721 --> 00:31:26.540
so for this book in
particular, I really

00:31:26.540 --> 00:31:32.330
looked to "Beloved" by Toni
Morrison because for one thing,

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:35.510
on a technical level, I was
trying to figure out how

00:31:35.510 --> 00:31:37.520
to work with past and present.

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:41.330
And in "Beloved," Toni Morrison
does this beautiful job

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:45.830
with memory, where she passes
seamlessly from the present day

00:31:45.830 --> 00:31:51.020
narrative into her character's
days as a slave and her journey

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:53.510
up north as a slave.

00:31:53.510 --> 00:31:56.330
And when I was writing
this, I literally

00:31:56.330 --> 00:31:57.890
had my little notebook.

00:31:57.890 --> 00:32:00.920
It was on the 20th
revision, or whatever.

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:04.250
I had my little notebook, and I
would copy out Toni Morrison's

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:06.620
sentences just to
sort of understand how

00:32:06.620 --> 00:32:09.050
she made those transitions--

00:32:09.050 --> 00:32:10.640
so "Beloved" by Toni Morrison.

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:12.170
I really like Zadie Smith.

00:32:12.170 --> 00:32:14.420
She's a British writer.

00:32:14.420 --> 00:32:19.351
And Anne Enright, her book, "The
Green Road" kind of influenced

00:32:19.351 --> 00:32:19.850
this.

00:32:19.850 --> 00:32:22.010
I like reading
writers whose voices

00:32:22.010 --> 00:32:24.680
are very different from my own.

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:27.440
It loosens up something
in me, creatively.

00:32:27.440 --> 00:32:28.400
SPEAKER 1: Wonderful.

00:32:28.400 --> 00:32:31.070
Well, we definitely want to
give the audience an opportunity

00:32:31.070 --> 00:32:32.270
to ask questions.

00:32:32.270 --> 00:32:34.049
AUDIENCE: I haven't
read your book yet,

00:32:34.049 --> 00:32:35.090
but I look forward to it.

00:32:35.090 --> 00:32:39.834
But I hear you telling the
stories of two brown women who

00:32:39.834 --> 00:32:42.500
have had the experience of being
immigrants or second generation

00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:44.185
immigrants in America.

00:32:44.185 --> 00:32:45.560
And then I hear
about your op-ed,

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:47.180
which talks about "The
Privileged Immigrant,"

00:32:47.180 --> 00:32:49.013
and then obviously, the
flip side of that is

00:32:49.013 --> 00:32:52.134
the unprivileged or
underprivileged immigrant--

00:32:52.134 --> 00:32:54.090
[COUGHS] sorry.

00:32:54.090 --> 00:32:56.894
So I was just wondering
what you think--

00:32:56.894 --> 00:32:58.310
why you think those
two narratives

00:32:58.310 --> 00:32:59.768
that sound so
similar at their root

00:32:59.768 --> 00:33:02.100
have developed so
differently in America,

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:06.060
and what we can learn
from deconstructing those?

00:33:06.060 --> 00:33:07.710
SHANTHI SEKARAN: So
the two narratives,

00:33:07.710 --> 00:33:12.840
they have evolved very
differently on American soil.

00:33:12.840 --> 00:33:15.600
To some extent, it's not
a matter of what country

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:21.870
you come, from it's a
matter of the structures

00:33:21.870 --> 00:33:25.240
that you've been able to
put in place for yourself.

00:33:25.240 --> 00:33:29.160
So if we talk about my
characters Kavya and Rishi,

00:33:29.160 --> 00:33:31.592
they own this little
house in Berkeley.

00:33:31.592 --> 00:33:34.050
They were able to buy that
house because their parents were

00:33:34.050 --> 00:33:36.540
able to help them
buy that house.

00:33:36.540 --> 00:33:39.730
And I never really go into what
their parents did for a living,

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:43.080
but the assumption
is that their parents

00:33:43.080 --> 00:33:44.220
were similar to my parents.

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:47.970
They came over in the '60s,
'70s, had good stable jobs,

00:33:47.970 --> 00:33:50.670
were able to accrue
some savings.

00:33:50.670 --> 00:33:54.240
And then, if you have
someone like Soli,

00:33:54.240 --> 00:33:58.480
she sort of kept her
money in her home.

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:00.420
She wasn't able to invest.

00:34:00.420 --> 00:34:01.980
And so much of this--

00:34:01.980 --> 00:34:04.950
so much of this just comes
down to the technicalities

00:34:04.950 --> 00:34:12.470
of money and land and the
neighborhoods and the schools

00:34:12.470 --> 00:34:14.219
that you're able to
send your children to.

00:34:14.219 --> 00:34:15.757
And I guess the choice--

00:34:15.757 --> 00:34:17.340
I guess really, what
it comes down to,

00:34:17.340 --> 00:34:20.190
is the power to choose
where you want to live

00:34:20.190 --> 00:34:22.170
and what you want
to do with your life

00:34:22.170 --> 00:34:23.612
and for your children.

00:34:23.612 --> 00:34:25.320
And I think that that
really has informed

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:28.325
the various trajectories
that we see in the US.

00:34:31.705 --> 00:34:34.080
SPEAKER 1: Just very quickly,
particularly on that point,

00:34:34.080 --> 00:34:37.409
in the op-ed in "The New York
Times," you mentioned that it's

00:34:37.409 --> 00:34:40.620
not one immigrant group is
better or stronger or more

00:34:40.620 --> 00:34:42.540
competent than the
other, but rather,

00:34:42.540 --> 00:34:44.110
the opportunities
or the path that

00:34:44.110 --> 00:34:46.050
was already created
for them in this nation

00:34:46.050 --> 00:34:47.457
before they come here.

00:34:47.457 --> 00:34:49.790
So I think that distinction
that you made was beautiful.

00:34:49.790 --> 00:34:52.440
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Thank you.

00:34:52.440 --> 00:34:55.250
AUDIENCE: So you
live in Berkeley,

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:57.940
and you've written
a book about a topic

00:34:57.940 --> 00:35:00.190
that, in some parts of the
country, kind of like plays

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:02.031
better, is better
accepted than maybe

00:35:02.031 --> 00:35:03.280
in other parts of the country.

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:07.160
And I'm curious if you're going
to other parts of the country

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:11.200
and if, in those places,
is this more or less

00:35:11.200 --> 00:35:12.460
of like a political novel?

00:35:12.460 --> 00:35:14.209
Is there some sort of
statement about that

00:35:14.209 --> 00:35:16.330
based on where you are,
who you're even talking

00:35:16.330 --> 00:35:17.920
with or talking to about it?

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:19.586
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Yeah,
so whether or not

00:35:19.586 --> 00:35:21.970
this is a political novel,
that usually comes down

00:35:21.970 --> 00:35:23.740
to the individual reader.

00:35:23.740 --> 00:35:25.630
So people who really
want to engage

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:27.790
with the political
aspects of this,

00:35:27.790 --> 00:35:30.250
they'll talk to me about that.

00:35:30.250 --> 00:35:33.270
And some people are just not
very politically engaged,

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:37.210
and so they see it for
the interpersonal drama

00:35:37.210 --> 00:35:38.290
of the book.

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:41.650
And in terms of traveling to
different parts of the country,

00:35:41.650 --> 00:35:43.300
I've been mostly
on the West Coast,

00:35:43.300 --> 00:35:47.710
and then, New York and DC,
but I did go down to Dallas.

00:35:47.710 --> 00:35:51.100
And I've been waiting for
the person with the red hat

00:35:51.100 --> 00:35:53.470
to stand up and ask
me some questions,

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:54.370
but they haven't yet.

00:35:57.010 --> 00:35:59.859
I find if--

00:35:59.859 --> 00:36:01.150
I assume that there is dissent.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:02.080
I assume that there
are going to be

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:03.850
people around who
don't like what

00:36:03.850 --> 00:36:06.392
I'm talking about in this book.

00:36:06.392 --> 00:36:07.850
But they haven't
said anything yet.

00:36:07.850 --> 00:36:10.100
And I think that,
like a lot of us,

00:36:10.100 --> 00:36:13.840
when they don't like something,
they're keeping quiet

00:36:13.840 --> 00:36:16.140
or they're just not
thinking about it.

00:36:16.140 --> 00:36:16.740
So that's--

00:36:16.740 --> 00:36:18.644
AUDIENCE: How would
you respond to that?

00:36:18.644 --> 00:36:20.920
SHANTHI SEKARAN: How would
I respond to that dissent?

00:36:20.920 --> 00:36:22.795
I'd first want to know
if they read the book.

00:36:22.795 --> 00:36:23.634
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:23.634 --> 00:36:24.300
SPEAKER 1: Fair.

00:36:24.300 --> 00:36:25.780
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Because
I feel like if you--

00:36:25.780 --> 00:36:27.670
when you engage
with someone's story

00:36:27.670 --> 00:36:31.070
and you really sort of connect
to them as a character,

00:36:31.070 --> 00:36:33.630
you start to see things
in a more complex way

00:36:33.630 --> 00:36:34.630
than you would normally.

00:36:37.390 --> 00:36:40.630
And I guess I would
want to listen

00:36:40.630 --> 00:36:45.170
to where they're coming from.

00:36:45.170 --> 00:36:47.320
I'm not the sort
of writer who can

00:36:47.320 --> 00:36:52.570
get into a political
argument with the reader.

00:36:52.570 --> 00:36:58.090
But I could talk to them about
the issues within the book.

00:36:58.090 --> 00:37:04.022
And really, I can't pretend
to want to convert people,

00:37:04.022 --> 00:37:05.730
but I want people to
understand that this

00:37:05.730 --> 00:37:08.400
is a more complex
situation than they

00:37:08.400 --> 00:37:10.110
may have initially assumed.

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:17.449
AUDIENCE: I'm curious-- you
mentioned that you're a teacher

00:37:17.449 --> 00:37:19.740
and you're a mother and you
wrote this book, obviously.

00:37:19.740 --> 00:37:22.080
I'm just curious how
you structured your time

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:25.110
and what a day in the
life is like when you're

00:37:25.110 --> 00:37:28.020
working on a book like this
that requires so much research

00:37:28.020 --> 00:37:29.835
and time and engagement?

00:37:29.835 --> 00:37:33.930
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Right,
yeah, so it was very slow.

00:37:33.930 --> 00:37:35.430
I should say I wrote
most of it when

00:37:35.430 --> 00:37:38.310
I had just one kid, not two.

00:37:38.310 --> 00:37:42.270
Because when you have two,
it's like you have 1,000.

00:37:42.270 --> 00:37:46.140
So basically, what I would
do is I would drop my kid off

00:37:46.140 --> 00:37:46.682
at preschool.

00:37:46.682 --> 00:37:48.390
I was teaching at the
same time, but only

00:37:48.390 --> 00:37:52.270
part-time at an
art college at CCA.

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:55.410
And so I would drop my
kid off at preschool,

00:37:55.410 --> 00:37:57.540
take BART into San Francisco.

00:37:57.540 --> 00:38:00.390
I used to go to the Writers'
Grotto in San Francisco

00:38:00.390 --> 00:38:02.074
to write a lot.

00:38:02.074 --> 00:38:03.990
So I'd have one or two
days where I would just

00:38:03.990 --> 00:38:08.020
spend the day there, and then
be back in Berkeley for the 4:00

00:38:08.020 --> 00:38:10.500
PM pickup at preschool.

00:38:10.500 --> 00:38:13.200
And so I had a couple of
days like this per week

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:16.440
that were just completely
devoted to the book.

00:38:16.440 --> 00:38:19.140
And slowly, slowly it builds.

00:38:19.140 --> 00:38:21.570
And at a certain point, you
get enough into the book

00:38:21.570 --> 00:38:23.530
that you can just write
anywhere at anytime.

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:29.231
You know, you can be standing
on a bus and writing, so yeah.

00:38:29.231 --> 00:38:31.230
AUDIENCE: How long did
the whole thing take you?

00:38:31.230 --> 00:38:33.354
SHANTHI SEKARAN: How long
did the whole thing take?

00:38:33.354 --> 00:38:36.030
So it took about 2 and
1/2 years for one draft.

00:38:36.030 --> 00:38:41.910
And then there was about 3 and
1/2 more years of reworking it

00:38:41.910 --> 00:38:43.550
and editing.

00:38:43.550 --> 00:38:46.380
Yeah, yeah, that was a
lot slower than I thought.

00:38:46.380 --> 00:38:50.040
I thought I'd like, write it,
and it'd be ready, but no.

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:51.540
AUDIENCE: I haven't
read the book,

00:38:51.540 --> 00:38:54.140
but I'm curious, how
do you sit on the title

00:38:54.140 --> 00:38:56.840
when there's these paths
of luck and un-luck,

00:38:56.840 --> 00:38:59.150
depending on the
different journeys

00:38:59.150 --> 00:39:02.259
and where their characters are
in their stages of their lives?

00:39:02.259 --> 00:39:03.800
SHANTHI SEKARAN:
Yeah, so the title--

00:39:03.800 --> 00:39:05.750
I never thought of lucky as--

00:39:05.750 --> 00:39:08.690
in terms of the
characters' journeys,

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:10.550
but I guess it
does apply to that.

00:39:10.550 --> 00:39:14.000
So "Lucky Boy"
refers, primarily,

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.450
to Ignazio, who's a
little boy born to Soli.

00:39:17.450 --> 00:39:23.660
And it has sort of an ironic
side, but also a sincere side.

00:39:23.660 --> 00:39:28.610
He's sincerely lucky because
he has these two mothers who

00:39:28.610 --> 00:39:30.680
love him and want him.

00:39:30.680 --> 00:39:32.750
And he's not so
lucky because it's

00:39:32.750 --> 00:39:36.140
this love that sort of
pulls apart his destiny.

00:39:36.140 --> 00:39:38.000
He doesn't know where
he's going to land,

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:42.144
or we don't know where
he's going to land, really.

00:39:42.144 --> 00:39:43.560
And in terms of
picking the title,

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:46.005
I think this was maybe
the fifth or sixth title

00:39:46.005 --> 00:39:47.715
that I settled on.

00:39:47.715 --> 00:39:50.090
SPEAKER 1: Can we ask what
some of the other titles were?

00:39:50.090 --> 00:39:53.810
SHANTHI SEKARAN: Oh, yeah, so
I think the first one, when

00:39:53.810 --> 00:39:56.060
I didn't really know where
this was going completely,

00:39:56.060 --> 00:39:59.041
was "Our Winning Smiles," which
is from the Belle and Sebastian

00:39:59.041 --> 00:39:59.540
song.

00:39:59.540 --> 00:40:02.540
I just-- I liked it.

00:40:02.540 --> 00:40:05.930
And then, there were
some not so great ones.

00:40:05.930 --> 00:40:09.200
But one of the other major
ones was "Season of the Beast,"

00:40:09.200 --> 00:40:11.780
because I--

00:40:11.780 --> 00:40:13.940
that image of the
beast comes up a lot,

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:15.650
but also there's
La Bestia, which

00:40:15.650 --> 00:40:18.620
is the freight train
that migrants ride up

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:19.790
through Mexico.

00:40:19.790 --> 00:40:22.940
They ride the top of it,
and it's pretty dangerous.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:24.590
That's in here, as well.

00:40:24.590 --> 00:40:27.500
And at one point--

00:40:27.500 --> 00:40:28.370
this is bad.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:30.500
So at one point--

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:33.230
Ignazio's nickname that his
mother gives him is Nacho.

00:40:33.230 --> 00:40:36.170
So at one point, it was
"Nacho!"-- exclamation mark.

00:40:39.770 --> 00:40:42.490
And then, eventually,
there is this one line

00:40:42.490 --> 00:40:45.630
that has the phrase
"Lucky Boy" in the book.

00:40:45.630 --> 00:40:48.800
And so eventually, I was like,
oh, OK, I'll just go with that.

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:52.749
And my editor wanted to change
it, and then we decided not to.

00:40:52.749 --> 00:40:54.540
SPEAKER 1: So thank
you so much for coming.

00:40:54.540 --> 00:40:55.390
We had a blast.

00:40:55.390 --> 00:40:56.390
We really appreciate it.

00:40:56.390 --> 00:40:57.806
SHANTHI SEKARAN:
Thanks, everyone.

00:40:57.806 --> 00:40:59.440
[APPLAUSE]

